  "sourceNotes": "Biscotti (from the Latin bis coctus, twice cooked) appear in Italian regional baking from the medieval period. The Tuscan cantucci, made with almonds, is the best-known form; chocolate and hazelnut variants became standard in northern Italian pasticcerie in the twentieth century. The twice-baked method is common to all versions and produces the characteristic dry crunch.",
